[{"id":"VR834522","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an electron moving horizontally to the right with velocity vector v between two horizontal parallel charged plates. The top plate is positively charged and the bottom plate is negatively charged.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834522.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An electron is moving with a horizontal velocity <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector v\"><math alttext=\"vector v\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mover><mi>v</mi><mo>â†’</mo></mover></math></span></span> toward two horizontal, parallel plates, as shown in the figure. The plates are made of a conducting material. The top plate has a positive charge, and the bottom plate has a negative charge of equal magnitude. Which of the following best represents the path of the electron when it is between the plates, and provides evidence or reasoning to support the claim? Assume that gravitational forces are negligible.</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup align:center cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1 colwidth:40\"/><col class=\"colspec colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:150\"/><col class=\"colspec align:left colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:150\"/><thead class=\"thead\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><th class=\"entry colname:col1\"></th><th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Electron Path</th><th class=\"entry colname:col3\">Evidence or Reasoning</th></tr></thead><tbody class=\"tbody valign:middle\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a curve that begins horizontal and gradually moves downward and to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834522.g02.svg\"/></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">The electric field is directed toward the bottom of the figure.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">B</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a curve that begins horizontal and gradually moves downward and to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834522.g03.svg\"/></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">The electron is attracted to the negative plate and repelled by the positive plate.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">C</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a curve that begins horizontal and gradually moves upward and to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834522.g04.svg\"/></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">The net force on the electron is toward the top of the figure.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">D</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a curve that begins horizontal and gradually moves upward and to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834522.g05.svg\"/></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">The potential energy of the electron-plate system is higher when the electron is closer to the positive plate.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR834522_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">A</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">B</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">C</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">D</p>"],"answer":2}]